<div id="review_3305675885" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3305675885" />
    <a title="Carol Roberts" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/106437735-carol-roberts"><img alt="Carol Roberts" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581463294p2/106437735.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3305675885?book_show_action=true">Apr 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol Roberts" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol Roberts" href="/user/show/106437735-carol-roberts">Carol Roberts</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3305675885" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13343009067070500538">William Hanna is an author on which I can always count to provide me with one of my favorite reads of the year. Such consistency is readers&apos; heaven to book addicts such as myself.<br/><br/>The thing I liked was that the book didn&apos;t immediately end after the main conflict did. It continued to check in with some of the most important characters (and by important, I mean important to society, not necessarily to the story itself), and had a bit of a romance! This surprised me, but I felt it was oddly appropri</span>
  <span id="freeText13343009067070500538" style="display:none">William Hanna is an author on which I can always count to provide me with one of my favorite reads of the year. Such consistency is readers' heaven to book addicts such as myself.<br /><br />The thing I liked was that the book didn't immediately end after the main conflict did. It continued to check in with some of the most important characters (and by important, I mean important to society, not necessarily to the story itself), and had a bit of a romance! This surprised me, but I felt it was oddly appropriate, it gave a hopeful ending to an otherwise sad, scary story. <br /><br />Reading a William Hanna’s, The Grim Reaper is like settling into a comfortable armchair before a crackling fireplace. The outside world drops away, and nothing seems to remain but the story. I became a devoted fan with the first novel I read and will continue to be one.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13343009067070500538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


